Initial idea:
  leveldb + sublevel
  sublevels:
    - meta - Hold info like version, other nodes having this, etc
    - data - Raw data contained at the key
  Upon startup, question peers for all local keys to ensure persistence & updates
  Upon receiving new data, send to 3 random other peers
  Each N hours (depends on future testing/decision), iterate over keys to ensure persistance (N copies in network) & fetch updates

Local storage:

  Have a flat local file with 2kiB "sectors"
  Pointers increment in 2kiB steps, giving a 4-byte pointer a range of 8 TiB (minus 2kiB)
  The size indicator for an entry is 4 bytes, making data blobs a maximum of 4 GiB (minus 1 byte)
  At the start of the file, we start directly with an entry

  Each entry has:
    256 4-byte pointers (1 kiB), each containing the sector in the file of the entry that contains the next character in it's key
    To follow a multi-byte keys, follow the pointers through the file
    If a pointer is set to 0, it is to be assumed as non-existing or unused

    The last 4 bytes of an entry (past the data blob) are a pointer to the start of the entry, allowing easy-access of the previous block
    when only the last block is known

    The 2nd kiB of the entry contains metadata about the entry.
      4-byte pointer to the next entry (0 for the last entry)
      4-byte size indicator of the data blob (0 for null, non-existing or empty)
      2-byte key size indicator
      0..1014 byte key of the current entry

    The previous/next pointers in the entry help checking if an update fits in the allotted space
    The previous/next pointer help with optimization, allowing a truncate of the database freeing disk-space

  When writing, either of 3 strategies may be employed
    Walk key path towards the key, update the data blob (and size) if the new data fits the block
    Scan through entries using next pointers, search for empty blocks large enough to contain the indicated data size
    Append the entry to the end of the file, force the key path to that location (and free old entry if it exists)

  When freeing/deleting an entry, the reference to it by the parent key should be removed and it should be merge by neighbour entries
    if those entries are free as well.

  When optimizing the database, all keys should be walked using the next pointers. If an empty/free entry has been found,
  continue following the next pointers until an entry has been found fitting inside the free entry. If no entries are found,
  relocate the next entry to the location of the free entry (and update the key tree). If an entry was found, relocate the found
  entry to the location of the free entry (and update the key tree)

DHT idea:
  ID/hash range is circular, as in 0x00 is one up from 0xFF
  Multiple types of keys
    Expiring -> max 1 day, data will expire (like dns records)
    Content-based hash
    Pubkey signed -> key = hash of pubkey, needs signature
  Basic network joining:
    Generate random ID (16 bits in this example, 256 bits in real life)
      0x6db7 -> 0110110110110111
    Join random node (bootstrap server?)
    Ask the node who is responsible for ID ^ (1<<{0..15})
      Store for future reference
    Ask the node who is responsible for ID-1
      Store as back reference, like 'previous' node
    Notify previous node we've joined the network
    Monitor next & previous nodes
  Getting key
    Contact first known node BELOW key
    Ask for it's key
  Writing random key
    Contact first known node BELOW key
    Send write request
  Being written to
    Write in local storage
    Send direct write to previous node
  Receiving direct write from next node
    Just write and keep monitoring
  Previous node goes down
    Ask network who's responsible now
    Notify that node of our presence
  Next node goes down
    We're responsible for it's keys now
    Send direct write for all local data to our previoius node
    Ask previous node who's responsible for key after new resposibility (& attempt connection)
  Get notification of new next node
    Send all local keys it's responsible for
    Store in our node list
